<section class="rw-content">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="rw-content-inner">

      <h2>Planning a Move Abroad? Your Savings Go Further Than You Think</h2>
      <p>The question most Americans ask when considering a move abroad is not whether they can afford it. It is whether their savings and income will last long enough to make the change stick. The answer depends almost entirely on where you go.</p>
      <p>In Vietnam or Egypt, a single person can live comfortably on $900 to $1,100 a month. In Portugal or Mexico, the same lifestyle runs $1,800 to $2,200. In Western Europe or Singapore, costs reach $3,000 or more. The spread is dramatic, and a modest savings account becomes a multi-year runway in the right country.</p>

      <h3>How the Calculator Works</h3>
      <p>The Runway Calculator takes your total savings, subtracts any monthly income you already have coming in, and divides the difference by the monthly cost of living in each country. That gives you a runway in months, adjusted for your lifestyle choice.</p>
      <p>The Lean setting (0.75x) reflects shared housing, mostly cooking at home, and minimal discretionary spending. Normal (1.0x) is a realistic mid-range budget that matches how most first-year expats actually spend. Comfortable (1.35x) covers a private apartment in a good neighborhood, regular dining out, and some local travel.</p>
      <p>When your monthly income covers your costs entirely, the calculator shows Indefinite because your savings will not decrease over time. That is the threshold for location-independent financial independence.</p>

      <h3>The Single vs. Couple Budget Gap</h3>
      <p>The couple budget is not double the single budget. Shared rent is the biggest factor, but internet, utilities, and some food costs also scale less than linearly. If you are moving with a partner, the per-person cost is noticeably lower than for a solo move, particularly in countries with high housing costs relative to other expenses.</p>

      <h3>What These Costs Do Not Include</h3>
      <p>The monthly figures cover rent, food, transport, utilities, and basic everyday spending. They do not include one-time relocation costs: flights, visa fees, international shipping, or a security deposit on a new apartment. Budget an additional $2,000 to $5,000 for those depending on your destination before your first full month abroad begins.</p>
      <p>Health insurance is also separate from these figures. US coverage does not apply internationally, so most expats add a SafetyWing or similar international policy for $45 to $150 per month depending on age and coverage tier.</p>

      <h3>Using This With the Country Match Quiz</h3>
      <p>The runway number tells you how long your savings last. The <a href="/country-match/quiz/">Country Match Quiz</a> tells you which countries actually fit your lifestyle, language preferences, climate, and visa situation. Running both tools together gives you a complete picture: which countries you can afford and which ones you will actually want to live in.</p>

      <div class="rw-faq">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="rw-faq-item">
          <p class="rw-faq-q">How is my monthly runway calculated?</p>
          <p class="rw-faq-a">We multiply the country's average monthly cost of living by your lifestyle factor (Lean 0.75x, Normal 1.0x, Comfortable 1.35x), then subtract your monthly income to get your net monthly burn rate. Dividing your total savings by that burn rate gives your runway in months.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rw-faq-item">
          <p class="rw-faq-q">What does "Indefinite" mean in the results?</p>
          <p class="rw-faq-a">Indefinite means your monthly income covers or exceeds the cost of living in that country at your chosen lifestyle level. Your savings remain intact indefinitely, which is the threshold for location-independent financial independence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rw-faq-item">
          <p class="rw-faq-q">Do these monthly costs include rent?</p>
          <p class="rw-faq-a">Yes. The figures represent a realistic all-in monthly budget including rent, food, transport, utilities, and basic everyday spending. They reflect mid-range living rather than backpacker minimums or luxury expat lifestyles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rw-faq-item">
          <p class="rw-faq-q">Should I choose Lean, Normal, or Comfortable?</p>
          <p class="rw-faq-a">Lean (0.75x) works for shared housing, cooking most meals at home, and minimal extras. Normal (1.0x) is a realistic mid-range baseline. Comfortable (1.35x) covers a private apartment in a good neighborhood, dining out regularly, and occasional local travel. Most people moving abroad for the first time land between Normal and Comfortable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rw-faq-item">
          <p class="rw-faq-q">Can I include remote work or freelance income?</p>
          <p class="rw-faq-a">Yes. The Monthly income field accepts any recurring income including remote salary, freelance revenue, Social Security, pension payments, or investment distributions. The calculator subtracts this from monthly costs before computing your runway.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script type="application/json" id="runway-data" set:html={budgetJSON}></script>

<script>
var BUDGET = JSON.parse(document.getElementById('runway-data').textContent);
var household = 'single';

(function initFromUrl() {
  var p = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
  var s = p.get('s'), inc = p.get('i'), h = p.get('h'), l = p.get('l');
  if (s) (document.getElementById('inp-savings') as HTMLInputElement).value = s;
  if (inc) (document.getElementById('inp-income') as HTMLInputElement).value = inc;
  if (h === 'couple') {
    household = 'couple';
    document.getElementById('btn-single').classList.remove('active');
    document.getElementById('btn-couple').classList.add('active');
  }
  if (l) {
    var lMap: Record<string, string> = { lean: '0.75', normal: '1', comfortable: '1.35' };
    var lVal = lMap[l];
    if (lVal) (document.getElementById('sel-lifestyle') as HTMLSelectElement).value = lVal;
  }
})();

function getInputs() {
  var savings = parseFloat((document.getElementById('inp-savings') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
  var income = parseFloat((document.getElementById('inp-income') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
  var mult = parseFloat((document.getElementById('sel-lifestyle') as HTMLSelectElement).value) || 1;
  return { savings, income, mult };
}

function fmtRunway(months: number): string {
  if (months === Infinity) return '<span class="rw-indefinite">Indefinite ∞</span>';
  var m = Math.floor(months);
  if (m < 1) return '&lt; 1 month';
  if (m < 24) return m + (m === 1 ? ' month' : ' months');
  var yrs = Math.floor(m / 12);
  var rem = m % 12;
  if (rem === 0) return yrs + (yrs === 1 ? ' year' : ' years');
  return yrs + 'y ' + rem + 'mo';
}

function compute() {
  var inp = getInputs();
  var results = BUDGET.map(function(c: any) {
    var budget = household === 'single' ? c.bs : c.bc;
    var cost = Math.round(budget * inp.mult);
    var burn = cost - inp.income;
    var runway = burn <= 0 ? Infinity : inp.savings / burn;
    return { slug: c.slug, name: c.name, iso2: c.iso2, cost, runway };
  });

  results.sort(function(a: any, b: any) {
    if (a.runway === Infinity && b.runway === Infinity) return a.cost - b.cost;
    if (a.runway === Infinity) return -1;
    if (b.runway === Infinity) return 1;
    if (b.runway !== a.runway) return b.runway - a.runway;
    return a.cost - b.cost;
  });

  document.getElementById('rw-count').textContent = results.length + ' countries';

  var badgeCls = ['rw-badge rw-badge-1', 'rw-badge rw-badge-2', 'rw-badge rw-badge-3'];
  var badgeLabels = ['1st', '2nd', '3rd'];

  document.getElementById('rw-grid').innerHTML = results.map(function(c: any, i: number) {
    var top = i < 3;
    var badge = top ? '<span class="' + badgeCls[i] + '">' + badgeLabels[i] + '</span>' : '';
    return '<a href="/countries/' + c.slug + '/" class="rw-card' + (top ? ' rw-card-top' : '') + '">' +
      badge +
      '<div class="rw-card-flag"><span class="fi fi-' + c.iso2 + '"></span></div>' +
      '<div class="rw-card-name">' + c.name + '</div>' +
      '<div class="rw-card-runway">' + fmtRunway(c.runway) + '</div>' +
      '<div class="rw-card-cost">$' + c.cost.toLocaleString() + '/mo</div>' +
      '</a>';
  }).join('');
}

document.getElementById('btn-single').addEventListener('click', function() {
  household = 'single';
  this.classList.add('active');
  document.getElementById('btn-couple').classList.remove('active');
  compute();
});
document.getElementById('btn-couple').addEventListener('click', function() {
  household = 'couple';
  this.classList.add('active');
  document.getElementById('btn-single').classList.remove('active');
  compute();
});
['inp-savings', 'inp-income', 'sel-lifestyle'].forEach(function(id) {
  document.getElementById(id).addEventListener('input', compute);
});

document.getElementById('btn-share-runway').addEventListener('click', function() {
  var inp = getInputs();
  var lKey = inp.mult <= 0.76 ? 'lean' : inp.mult >= 1.34 ? 'comfortable' : 'normal';
  var url = window.location.origin + '/runway/?s=' + inp.savings + '&i=' + inp.income + '&h=' + household + '&l=' + lKey;
  if (navigator.clipboard && navigator.clipboard.writeText) {
    navigator.clipboard.writeText(url).then(showCopied).catch(function() { fallbackCopy(url); });
  } else {
    fallbackCopy(url);
  }
});

function showCopied() {
  var el = document.getElementById('rw-copied');
  el.textContent = 'Link copied to clipboard!';
  setTimeout(function() { el.textContent = ''; }, 3000);
}
function fallbackCopy(url: string) {
  var ta = document.createElement('textarea');
  ta.value = url;
  ta.style.cssText = 'position:fixed;opacity:0;pointer-events:none';
  document.body.appendChild(ta);
  ta.select();
  document.execCommand('copy');
  document.body.removeChild(ta);
  showCopied();
}

compute();
</script>

</BaseLayout>
